00020  @page viewzilla Performance Profiling using Viewzilla
00021 
00022 @section viewzilla_intro 1. Introduction
00023 
00024     Performance profiling of the OCTEON processor cores and support hardware
00025     can help the application programmer to optimize for OCTEON. Cavium Inc.
00026     provides the tool @b Viewzilla to help the programmer to gather and
00027     visualize this profiling data.
00028 
00029     This document provides detailed information on the following aspects of
00030     Viewzilla:
00031 
00032     - @ref viewzilla_intro
00033     - @ref viewzilla_features
00034     - @ref viewzilla_starting
00035     - @ref viewzilla_interface
00036     - @ref viewzilla_instruction_decode
00037     - @ref viewzilla_checklist
00038     - @ref viewzilla_utilities
00039 
00040 @section viewzilla_features 2. Features
00041 
00042     -# Visual representation of each processor's pipeline
00043     -# Detailed load for each processor's crypto engine (-modes=cryptovz for the simulator)
00044     -# Level 1 and Level 2 cache operations
00045     -# Coherent bus utilization
00046     -# Low latency memory bandwidth utilization
00047     -# C Source display
00048     -# Instruction tracing per processor or all processors
00049     -# Fast searching
00050     -# Loop visualization with instruction stepping
00051     -# Quickly scale view from high level overview down to individual instructions
00052 
00053 @section viewzilla_starting 3. Starting Viewzilla
00054 
00055     Viewzilla requires an OCTEON @b vz file and can optionally use debugging
00056     information from ELF executables. The basic viewzilla command line syntax
00057     is:
00058 
00059     @code
00060         $ viewzilla octeon.vz [elf] [elf] ...
00061     @endcode
00062 
00063     - octeon.vz
00064         - Viewzilla file to load. Generated by the oct-sim option @b -vz. The
00065             option @b -modes=cryptovz can also be used to detail the crypto
00066             units.
00067     - [elf]
00068         - Optional Mips ELF files to load debugging information from
00069 
00070     Applications should be build with DWARF debugging information
00071     (@b -g compiler option).
00072 
00073 @section viewzilla_interface 4. The User Interface
00074 
00075     Below is a sample of the viewzilla interface showing the output of the
00076     passthrough example.
00077 
00078     @image html viewzilla_screen.png
00079 
00080     Here are the functions of the screen elements:
00081     -# Pull down menus
00082         - @b File - @b Find can be used to find arbitrary strings in the
00083             viewzilla file. Searching starts at the current cycle and continues
00084             forward through time. Searches are case sensitive.
00085             Short cut keys: @b Control-F, @b /
00086         - @b File - @b Find @b Next continues the previous find.
00087             Short cut keys: @b Control-G, @b n
00088         - @b File - @b Quit exits the viewzilla program.
00089         - @b Show - @b Source uses the DWARF debugging information from the
00090             ELF files to show the original program source.
00091         - @b Show - @b Processor @b Instructions displays the instruction
00092             trace annotated by source for the current selected processor.
00093         - @b Show - @b All @b Processor @b Instructions displays the instruction
00094             traces annotated by source for all the running processors.
00095         - @b Show - @b Highlight @b Next moves the highlight to the next active
00096             cycle for the selected hardware unit.
00097             Short cut keys: @b ->, @b k
00098         - @b Show - @b Highlight @b Previous moves the highlight to the previous
00099             active cycle for the selected hardware unit.
00100             Short cut keys: @b <-, @b j
00101         - @b Show - @b Hardware controls whether each hardware unit is
00102             displayed.
00103     -# Start cycle input field
00104         - This is the first clock cycle displayed at the left edge of the
00105             cycle view window. This value may be modified by directly typing
00106             a value, scrolling the horizontal scrollbar, or through one of the
00107             searching operations.
00108     -# Selected box description
00109         - Whenever the mouse moves over an active cycle this shows a short
00110             description of what is occurring.
00111     -# Ending cycle
00112         - This is the last cycle visible in the cycle view window. It is
00113             calculated based on the current zoom level and window width.
00114     -# Cycle view window
00115         - This window display each hardware unit (vertically axis) and its
00116             state at each cycle (horizontal axis). Moving the mouse over boxes
00117             will show a short description. Clicking on a box will select it,
00118             any boxes associated with it, and display source/instructions as
00119             available. You can step to the next / previous selection using the
00120             left and right arrow keys.
00121     -# Vertical scrollbar for the cycle view window
00122         - If the viewzilla window is too small, not all hardware units can be
00123             display in the cycle view window. Use this scrollbar to control
00124             which one are available.
00125     -# Zoom level slider
00126         - Use this slider to control how much information is displayed. Sliding
00127             it up shows fewer cycles, but more detail. Sliding it down provides
00128             more cycles, but less detail.
00129     -# Horizontal scrollbar for the cycle view window
00130         - Use this scrollbar to quickly move to any cycle in the viewzilla
00131             trace. The left and right arrows move one cycle at a time. Click
00132             paging moves 3/4 of the view area at a time.
00133     -# Source / Instruction display window
00134         - Depending on the selection in the @b Show pulldown this will
00135             either display the source file for the current instruction or an
00136             instruction trace with source annotation. Note: This is only
00137             available when an instruction is selected.
00138     -# Vertical scrollbar for the source window
00139         - Use this to scroll through the loaded source file or instruction
00140             trace.

00142 @section viewzilla_instruction_decode 5. Decoding Instruction Information
00143 
00144     When you click on a processor instruction, you will see text detailing
00145     the state of the processor at execution time. Here are some examples and
00146     how to decode them:
00147 
00148 @verbatim
00149     PP0:20001254<main+116>:2400@0~MisP   : [24a50001] ADDIU   $a1, $a1, 1 [$a1=2]
00150 @endverbatim
00151 
00152     -# PP0
00153         - This is for core 0
00154     -# 20001254<main+116>
00155         - The instruction virtual address (hex + label)
00156     -# 2400@@0
00157         - Cycle 2400, issued on pipe 0
00158     -# ~MisP
00159         - The instruction was delayed due to a branch mispredict
00160     -# 24a50001
00161         - Hex of the instruction
00162     -# ADDIU   $a1, $a1, 1
00163         - Instruction mnemonic
00164 
00165 @verbatim
00166     PP0:20001264<main+132>:7302@0~DWB    : [dfbf0000] LD      $ra, 0($sp) [$ra=20000264(7FFFFFD0,7FFFFFD0)]
00167 @endverbatim
00168 
00169     -# ~DWB
00170         - This load missed and matched a pending write buffer
00171     -# (7FFFFFD0,7FFFFFD0)
00172         - (virtual address,physical address) in hex
00173     -# $ra=20000264
00174         - 0x20000264 was loaded from physical address 0x7FFFFFD0
00175 
00176 @verbatim
00177     PP0:200004EC<flush_print+ 36>:7383@0~SL     : [ffb00000] SD      $s0, 0($sp) [(7FFFFFD0,7FFFFFD0)=0]
00178 @endverbatim
00179 
00180     -# ~SL
00181         - The instruction was delayed because it had to issue on pipe 0
00182     -# (7FFFFFD0,7FFFFFD0)
00183         - (virtual address,physical address) in hex
00184     -# =0
00185         - The value 0 was written to physical address 0x7FFFFFD0
00186 
00187     List of stall reasons:
00188     - ~ITLB   = Instruction TLB miss
00189     - ~BR     = Prior branch instruction
00190     - ~JR     = Prior jump instruction
00191     - ~MisP   = Prior branch mispredicted
00192     - ~MTCOP0 = Prior MT COP0 instruction
00193     - ~IF     = Instruction fetch
00194     - ~SL     = Needs pipe 0, but pipe 1 is available
00195     - ~BRF    = Ignore this
00196     - ~RAW    = Input register values not available
00197     - ~MisJR  = Mispredicted jump
00198     - ~WAI    = WAIT instruction
00199     - ~MUL    = Multiplier busy
00200     - ~CR     = Crypto busy
00201     - ~LLM    = LLM busy
00202     - ~D      = Dcache miss that does not hit a write buffer entry
00203     - ~DWB    = Dcache miss that does hit a write buffer entry
00204     - ~SY     = SYNC/SYNCS/SYNCIOBDMA instruction
00205 
00206 @section viewzilla_checklist 6. Checklist for Best Results
00207 
00208     -# Generate the viewzilla input file with the @b -vz option to @b oct-sim.
00209     -# Instruction tracing is already contained in the viewzilla file. Use
00210         @b -quiet with @b oct-sim to suppress tracing.
00211     -# Most of the time you are only interested in application performance.
00212         Use the option @b -wait=main to skip all analysis before the main
00213         entry point of the program. Without this option, it can be difficult
00214         to wade through all the output for the bootloader and C library
00215         startup.
00216     -# The simulator runs much slower with viewzilla output turned on. Use the
00217         @b -wait option to only start output in the area you are interested
00218         in.
00219     -# Viewzilla output files can get large very quickly. Make sure you
00220         have lots of free disk space. As an example, booting 16 cores and
00221         running for 10 million cycles generates a @b 14GB output file.
00222     -# Compile applications with debugging symbols (@b -g)
00223     -# Viewzilla uses the full pathnames present in the DWARF debugging
00224         information. Make sure source code can be found at these locations. If
00225         source view is unable to find a file it will show the path it tried.
00226     -# Due to the large amount of data, searching through a viewzilla trace
00227         can be slow. Avoid long searches by scrolling to the approximate cycle
00228         where your search can be found.
00229 
00230 @section viewzilla_utilities 7. Viewzilla related utilities
00231 
00232     The vz-cut utility is provided to easily copy a section out of a viewzilla file
00233     into a smaller file.  The input file is not modified.
00234 
00235      @code
00236          $ vz-cut --start start_cycle --end end_cycle [--filename input_filename] [--outfilename output_filename] [--help]
00237      @endcode
00238 
00239      - --start: the cycle to start copying from
00240      - --end:   the cycle to end copying on
00241      - --filename: input filename, defaults to 'octeon.vz' if not provided
00242      - --outfilename: output filename, defaults to 'octeon-cut.vz' if not provided
00243      - --help:  displays help message.
00244 
00245     @note Only one of start or end is required, as start defaults to 0 and end defaults to the end of the file
00246     if the other is not provided.
00247
